
# PHASE 11 — LGTM OBSERVABILITY STACK

[## [SECTION: Step 1 — Install the Observability Namespace (Component #151)]]


1
04:06:54,000 --> 04:07:00,000
Now let's move to Phase 11. End-to-end observability.
Logs, metrics, traces, and alerts all connected.

2
04:07:00,000 --> 04:07:06,000
First, create the observability namespace.
kubectl create namespace observability

3
04:07:06,000 --> 04:07:12,000
Create the monitoring namespace if not already created.
kubectl create namespace monitoring

4
04:07:12,000 --> 04:07:18,000
Now install the LGTM stack via Helm.
Loki for logs, Grafana for dashboards, Tempo for traces, Mimir for metrics.

5
04:07:18,000 --> 04:07:24,000
Add the Grafana Helm repository.
helm repo add grafana https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts

6
04:07:24,000 --> 04:07:30,000
Install Loki for log aggregation.
helm upgrade dash dash install loki grafana/loki with namespace observability.

7
04:07:30,000 --> 04:07:36,000
Set loki.storage.type to s3.
Set bucket names for chunks and ruler. Set region to us-east-1.

8
04:07:36,000 --> 04:07:42,000
Install Tempo for distributed tracing storage.
helm upgrade dash dash install tempo grafana/tempo-distributed with namespace observability.

9
04:07:42,000 --> 04:07:48,000
Set storage.trace.backend to s3.
Set bucket name and region.

10
04:07:48,000 --> 04:07:54,000
Install Mimir for long-term metrics.
helm upgrade dash dash install mimir grafana/mimir-distributed with namespace observability.

11
04:07:54,000 --> 04:08:00,000
Set mimir structured config common storage backend to s3.
Set bucket name and region.

12
04:08:00,000 --> 04:08:06,000
Install Grafana for visualization.
helm upgrade dash dash install grafana grafana/grafana with namespace observability.

13
04:08:06,000 --> 04:08:12,000
Set persistence enabled to true.
Set admin password from environment variable.

14
04:08:12,000 --> 04:08:18,000
Configure datasources using the datasources.yaml file.
Our LGTM stack is installed.


[## [SECTION: Step 2 — OpenTelemetry Dependencies (Component #157)]]


15
04:08:18,000 --> 04:08:24,000
Now add OpenTelemetry dependencies to pyproject.toml.

16
04:08:24,000 --> 04:08:30,000
Add opentelemetry-api version 1.24.0 or higher.
Add opentelemetry-sdk version 1.24.0 or higher.

17
04:08:30,000 --> 04:08:36,000
Add opentelemetry-exporter-otlp-proto-grpc version 1.24.0 or higher.
This exports traces to the OpenTelemetry Collector.

18
04:08:36,000 --> 04:08:42,000
Add opentelemetry-instrumentation-fastapi version 0.45b0 or higher.
This instruments FastAPI automatically.

19
04:08:42,000 --> 04:08:48,000
Add opentelemetry-instrumentation-sqlalchemy version 0.45b0 or higher.
This instruments SQLAlchemy queries.

20
04:08:48,000 --> 04:08:54,000
Add opentelemetry-instrumentation-redis version 0.45b0 or higher.
This instruments Redis calls.

21
04:08:54,000 --> 04:09:00,000
Add opentelemetry-instrumentation-httpx version 0.45b0 or higher.
This instruments HTTPX requests to LLM APIs.

22
04:09:00,000 --> 04:09:06,000
Add opentelemetry-instrumentation-logging version 0.45b0 or higher.
This injects trace IDs into logs.

23
04:09:06,000 --> 04:09:12,000
Install the dependencies.
pip install minus e dot dev.

24
04:09:12,000 --> 04:09:18,000
Our OpenTelemetry dependencies are ready.
Now let's configure the tracer provider.


[## [SECTION: Step 3 — Tracer Provider Configuration (Components #158–165)]]


25
04:09:18,000 --> 04:09:24,000
Now let's create the tracer provider configuration.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/telemetry/tracing.py

26
04:09:24,000 --> 04:09:30,000
First, imports. We need logging and os.
From opentelemetry, we import trace.

27
04:09:30,000 --> 04:09:36,000
From opentelemetry.exporter.otlp.proto.grpc.trace_exporter, import OTLPSpanExporter.
This exports spans to the OpenTelemetry Collector.

28
04:09:36,000 --> 04:09:42,000
From opentelemetry.instrumentation.fastapi, import FastAPIInstrumentor.
From opentelemetry.instrumentation.httpx, import HTTPXClientInstrumentor.

29
04:09:42,000 --> 04:09:48,000
From opentelemetry.instrumentation.logging, import LoggingInstrumentor.
From opentelemetry.instrumentation.redis, import RedisInstrumentor.

30
04:09:48,000 --> 04:09:54,000
From opentelemetry.instrumentation.sqlalchemy, import SQLAlchemyInstrumentor.
From opentelemetry.sdk.resources, import Resource.

31
04:09:54,000 --> 04:10:00,000
From opentelemetry.sdk.trace, import TracerProvider.
From opentelemetry.sdk.trace.export, import BatchSpanProcessor, ConsoleSpanExporter.

32
04:10:00,000 --> 04:10:06,000
From opentelemetry.sdk.trace.sampling, import ParentBased, TraceIdRatioBased.

33
04:10:06,000 --> 04:10:12,000
Now define the configure_tracing function.
It takes an optional FastAPI app and optional SQLAlchemy engine.

34
04:10:12,000 --> 04:10:18,000
First, create the resource.
It identifies this service in all traces.

35
04:10:18,000 --> 04:10:24,000
Resource includes service name, service version, service namespace.
Deployment environment, Kubernetes namespace, and Kubernetes pod name.

36
04:10:24,000 --> 04:10:30,000
Next, create the sampler.
ParentBased with root TraceIdRatioBased at SAMPLING_RATE.

37
04:10:30,000 --> 04:10:36,000
SAMPLING_RATE defaults to 0.01 which is 1 percent.
This means 99 percent of successful, fast traces are dropped at the SDK before export.

38
04:10:36,000 --> 04:10:42,000
The OpenTelemetry Collector then applies tail sampling.
After seeing the full trace, it keeps 100 percent of error traces regardless of head sampling.

39
04:10:42,000 --> 04:10:48,000
Create the TracerProvider with resource and sampler.
Create the OTLP exporter pointing to the OpenTelemetry Collector.

40
04:10:48,000 --> 04:10:54,000
Set insecure equals True for development, False for production.
Add a batch span processor to the provider.

41
04:10:54,000 --> 04:11:00,000
If environment is dev, add a console exporter for local debugging.
Set the provider as the global tracer provider.

42
04:11:00,000 --> 04:11:06,000
Now instrument FastAPI.
Call FastAPIInstrumentor.instrument_app with the app.

43
04:11:06,000 --> 04:11:12,000
Exclude health and metrics endpoints.
They generate thousands of spans with zero debugging value.

44
04:11:12,000 --> 04:11:18,000
Add a server request hook to tag agent spans.
If the path contains slash query, set component to query-endpoint.

45
04:11:18,000 --> 04:11:24,000
Now instrument SQLAlchemy.
Call SQLAlchemyInstrumentor.instrument with the sync engine.

46
04:11:24,000 --> 04:11:30,000
Enable commenter to add traceparent comment to SQL queries.
This allows you to find the exact trace ID from a slow query log.

47
04:11:30,000 --> 04:11:36,000
Now instrument Redis.
Call RedisInstrumentor.instrument.

48
04:11:36,000 --> 04:11:42,000
Now instrument httpx.
Call HTTPXClientInstrumentor.instrument with a request hook.

49
04:11:42,000 --> 04:11:48,000
The request hook adds LLM provider info to outbound spans.
If the URL contains openai, set llm.provider to openai.

50
04:11:48,000 --> 04:11:54,000
If the URL contains groq, set llm.provider to groq.
If the URL contains azure, set llm.provider to azure-openai.

51
04:11:54,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Finally, instrument logging.
LoggingInstrumentor.instrument with set_logging_format equals True.

52
04:12:00,000 --> 04:12:06,000
This adds trace_id and span_id to every Python log record.
Combined with Loki's Grafana datasource, you can click a log line and jump directly to the trace.

53
04:12:06,000 --> 04:12:12,000
Define the get_tracer function.
It returns a named tracer for manual instrumentation.

54
04:12:12,000 --> 04:12:18,000
Now wire it into server.py lifespan.
Call configure_tracing before initialising dependencies.

55
04:12:18,000 --> 04:12:24,000
This ensures DB connection spans are captured from the start.
Our tracer provider configuration is complete.


[## [SECTION: Step 4 — Custom RAG Spans (Components #162–164)]]


56
04:12:24,000 --> 04:12:30,000
Auto-instrumentation covers HTTP, DB, and Redis.
The RAG-specific operations need manual spans.

57
04:12:30,000 --> 04:12:36,000
First, add spans to the embedding client.
In embeddings.py, import get_tracer from telemetry.

58
04:12:36,000 --> 04:12:42,000
Create a tracer named financial_rag.embeddings.
In embed_texts, create a span named rag.embedding.

59
04:12:42,000 --> 04:12:48,000
Set attributes on the span.
embedding.provider, embedding.text_count, embedding.dimensions.

60
04:12:48,000 --> 04:12:54,000
This shows exactly how long embedding takes for each batch.

61
04:12:54,000 --> 04:13:00,000
Next, add spans to the hybrid searcher.
In hybrid_search.py, import get_tracer from telemetry.

62
04:13:00,000 --> 04:13:06,000
Create a tracer named financial_rag.search.
In the search method, create a span named rag.search.

63
04:13:06,000 --> 04:13:12,000
Set attributes. search.type, search.question_length, search.alpha.
After the search, set search.results_count.

64
04:13:12,000 --> 04:13:18,000
This shows how long vector and text search take combined.

65
04:13:18,000 --> 04:13:24,000
Next, add spans to the query engine.
In query_engine.py, import get_tracer from telemetry.

66
04:13:24,000 --> 04:13:30,000
Create a tracer named financial_rag.llm.
In _generate_answer, create a span named rag.llm.

67
04:13:30,000 --> 04:13:36,000
Set attributes. llm.model, llm.provider, llm.analysis_style, llm.context_length.
This shows exactly how long LLM inference takes.

68
04:13:36,000 --> 04:13:42,000
These three spans produce a flame graph in Jaeger.
It shows exactly where time is spent in a RAG query.

69
04:13:42,000 --> 04:13:48,000
HTTP POST slash query takes 400 milliseconds total.
rag.embedding takes 45 milliseconds.

70
04:13:48,000 --> 04:13:54,000
rag.search takes 180 milliseconds.
pgvector query takes 90 milliseconds automatically from SQLAlchemy instrumentation.

71
04:13:54,000 --> 04:14:00,000
redis get takes 5 milliseconds automatically from Redis instrumentation.
rag.llm takes 170 milliseconds.

72
04:14:00,000 --> 04:14:06,000
httpx POST takes 165 milliseconds automatically from httpx instrumentation.
Our custom RAG spans are complete.


[## [SECTION: Step 5 — OpenTelemetry Collector (Component #158)]]


73
04:14:06,000 --> 04:14:12,000
Now let's configure the OpenTelemetry Collector.
We'll put it in observability/tracing/tracer-provider.yaml

74
04:14:12,000 --> 04:14:18,000
The collector receives traces from the FastAPI application.
It processes and exports them to multiple backends.

75
04:14:18,000 --> 04:14:24,000
Receivers. otlp protocol with grpc on port 4317 and http on port 4318.

76
04:14:24,000 --> 04:14:30,000
Processors. resource adds attributes to all spans.
service.namespace to financial-rag, deployment.environment from namespace.

77
04:14:30,000 --> 04:14:36,000
Batch processor for performance.
timeout 5 seconds, send batch size 1024, send batch max size 2048.

78
04:14:36,000 --> 04:14:42,000
Tail sampling processor. This is the most important part.

79
04:14:42,000 --> 04:14:48,000
decision_wait is 10 seconds. num_traces is 100000.
expected_new_traces_per_sec is 500.

80
04:14:48,000 --> 04:14:54,000
Policies. errors-policy based on status code.
Keep 100 percent of error traces.

81
04:14:54,000 --> 04:15:00,000
slow-traces-policy based on latency threshold 2000 milliseconds.
Keep 100 percent of slow traces.

82
04:15:00,000 --> 04:15:06,000
llm-traces-policy based on string attribute component equals llm-client or agent.
Keep 100 percent of LLM-related traces.

83
04:15:06,000 --> 04:15:12,000
probabilistic-policy with sampling percentage 1 percent.
Keep only 1 percent of everything else.

84
04:15:12,000 --> 04:15:18,000
Memory limiter prevents OOM on trace bursts.
Check interval 1 second, limit 512 megabytes, spike limit 128 megabytes.

85
04:15:18,000 --> 04:15:24,000
Exporters. jaeger for in-cluster trace visualization.
endpoint is jaeger-collector.monitoring.svc.cluster.local port 14250.

86
04:15:24,000 --> 04:15:30,000
awsxray for prod trace storage with 30-day retention.
region us-east-1.

87
04:15:30,000 --> 04:15:36,000
prometheus exporter for trace-based metrics.
endpoint port 8889, namespace financial_rag.

88
04:15:36,000 --> 04:15:42,000
Service pipelines.
traces pipeline uses otlp receiver, memory_limiter, resource, tail_sampling, batch processors.
Exporters are jaeger and awsxray.

89
04:15:42,000 --> 04:15:48,000
Metrics pipeline uses otlp receiver, memory_limiter, resource, batch processors.
Exporter is prometheus.

90
04:15:48,000 --> 04:15:54,000
Apply the collector configuration.
kubectl apply -f observability/tracing/tracer-provider.yaml

91
04:15:54,000 --> 04:16:00,000
Apply Jaeger for dev and staging.
kubectl apply -f observability/tracing/jaeger-install.yaml

92
04:16:00,000 --> 04:16:06,000
Our OpenTelemetry Collector is complete.
Traces now flow from the application to Jaeger and X-Ray.


[## [SECTION: Step 6 — Structured JSON Logging (Component #166)]]


93
04:16:06,000 --> 04:16:12,000
Now let's add structured JSON logging.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/api/logging_config.py

94
04:16:12,000 --> 04:16:18,000
First, imports. We need logging and structlog.
From opentelemetry, we import trace.

95
04:16:18,000 --> 04:16:24,000
Define the configure_logging function.
It loads settings from get_settings.

96
04:16:24,000 --> 04:16:30,000
Define shared_processors list.
structlog.contextvars.merge_contextvars, structlog.stdlib.add_logger_name.

97
04:16:30,000 --> 04:16:36,000
structlog.stdlib.add_log_level, structlog.processors.TimeStamper with fmt iso.
And _add_trace_context to inject trace ID and span ID.

98
04:16:36,000 --> 04:16:42,000
If LOG_FORMAT is json, add JSONRenderer for production.
If not, add ConsoleRenderer for development.

99
04:16:42,000 --> 04:16:48,000
Configure structlog with the processors.
Set wrapper_class to structlog.make_filtering_bound_logger with the log level.

100
04:16:48,000 --> 04:16:54,000
Set logger_factory to structlog.PrintLoggerFactory.

101
04:16:54,000 --> 04:17:00,000
Now define the _add_trace_context function.
It gets the current span from OpenTelemetry.

102
04:17:00,000 --> 04:17:06,000
If the span exists and is recording, add trace_id and span_id to the event_dict.
Format trace_id as 32 hex characters, span_id as 16 hex characters.

103
04:17:06,000 --> 04:17:12,000
Call configure_logging at the start of the lifespan function.
Before any other imports that might call logging.getLogger.

104
04:17:12,000 --> 04:17:18,000
Our structured logging is complete.
Every log line now contains trace_id and span_id for correlation.


[## [SECTION: Step 7 — SLO Recording Rules and Alerts (Components #172–173)]]


105
04:17:18,000 --> 04:17:24,000
Now let's create SLO recording rules and alerts.
We'll put them in observability/slo/slo-rules.yaml

106
04:17:24,000 --> 04:17:30,000
Three SLOs defined.

107
04:17:30,000 --> 04:17:36,000
SLO-1. API availability at 99.5 percent.
Error budget over 30 days is 3.65 hours of downtime.

108
04:17:36,000 --> 04:17:42,000
SLO-2. Query latency P99 under 120 seconds for 95 percent of requests.
5 percent of requests can be slow.

109
04:17:42,000 --> 04:17:48,000
SLO-3. Ingestion success rate at 99 percent over 7 days.
1 percent of filings can fail.

110
04:17:48,000 --> 04:17:54,000
First, recording rules for SLO-1 availability.
good requests equals non-5xx status codes.

111
04:17:54,000 --> 04:18:00,000
record financial_rag:api_request_success:rate5m.
Sum of rate of successful requests divided by sum of rate of all requests.

112
04:18:00,000 --> 04:18:06,000
Record error rates for different time windows.
1 hour, 6 hours, 24 hours, and 72 hours.

113
04:18:06,000 --> 04:18:12,000
Now alerting rules for SLO-1.
Fast burn alert at 14.4 times the error rate.

114
04:18:12,000 --> 04:18:18,000
Burns 2 percent of monthly budget in 1 hour.
Pages immediately.

115
04:18:18,000 --> 04:18:24,000
Slow burn alert at 6 times the error rate.
Burns 5 percent of monthly budget in 6 hours.
Warning level, investigate today.

116
04:18:24,000 --> 04:18:30,000
Now SLO-2 for query latency.
Use http_request_duration_seconds_bucket with le 120.

117
04:18:30,000 --> 04:18:36,000
Calculate the ratio of requests under 120 seconds.
Same multi-window multi-burn-rate approach.

118
04:18:36,000 --> 04:18:42,000
SLO-3 for ingestion success.
Record financial_rag:ingestion_success_rate:rate24h.

119
04:18:42,000 --> 04:18:48,000
Sum of processed total divided by sum of processed total plus failed total.
Alert if success rate is below 99 percent for 30 minutes.

120
04:18:48,000 --> 04:18:54,000
Now create the SLO alerting rules in a separate file.
observability/slo/slo-alerts.yaml

121
04:18:54,000 --> 04:19:00,000
Page alert when burns more than 2 percent budget in 1 hour.
Fast burn 14.4 times error rate.

122
04:19:00,000 --> 04:19:06,000
Warning alert when burns more than 5 percent budget in 6 hours.
Slow burn 6 times error rate.

123
04:19:06,000 --> 04:19:12,000
Apply the rules.
kubectl apply -f observability/slo/slo-rules.yaml
kubectl apply -f observability/slo/slo-alerts.yaml

124
04:19:12,000 --> 04:19:18,000
Our SLO recording rules and alerts are complete.
Error budget is now monitored and alertable.


[## [SECTION: Step 8 — ArgoCD Notifications (Component #116 wiring)]]


125
04:19:18,000 --> 04:19:24,000
Now let's configure ArgoCD notifications.
We'll put them in argocd/notifications/templates.yaml

126
04:19:24,000 --> 04:19:30,000
First, define the Slack service.
token from environment variable, username ArgoCD, icon colon argo colon.

127
04:19:30,000 --> 04:19:36,000
Define the PagerDuty service.
serviceKeys with prod-oncall from environment variable.

128
04:19:36,000 --> 04:19:42,000
Define the app-sync-succeeded template.
Slack attachment with green color.
Title shows the app name synced.
Fields include environment and revision.

129
04:19:42,000 --> 04:19:48,000
Define the app-sync-failed template.
Slack attachment with red color.
Title shows the app name sync FAILED.
Fields include environment and error message.

130
04:19:48,000 --> 04:19:54,000
PagerDuty summary. ArgoCD sync failed colon app name.
Severity error.

131
04:19:54,000 --> 04:20:00,000
Define the app-health-degraded template.
Slack attachment with yellow color.
Title shows the app name health DEGRADED.
Field includes health status.

132
04:20:00,000 --> 04:20:06,000
PagerDuty summary. App degraded colon app name.
Severity warning.

133
04:20:06,000 --> 04:20:12,000
Define triggers.
on-sync-succeeded triggers when operationState phase is Succeeded.
on-sync-failed triggers when operationState phase is Error or Failed.
on-health-degraded triggers when health status is Degraded.

134
04:20:12,000 --> 04:20:18,000
Set default triggers to on-sync-failed and on-health-degraded.
Sync succeeded is optional, only for info.

135
04:20:18,000 --> 04:20:24,000
Apply the notifications.
kubectl apply -f argocd/notifications/templates.yaml

136
04:20:24,000 --> 04:20:30,000
The PagerDuty integration only fires on prod application failures.
The annotation uses environment-oncall which only resolves in prod.

137
04:20:30,000 --> 04:20:36,000
Our ArgoCD notifications are complete.
Deployment status now goes to Slack and PagerDuty.


[## [SECTION: Step 9 — OPA Rego Policies (CI enforcement)]]


138
04:20:36,000 --> 04:20:42,000
Now let's create OPA Rego policies for CI enforcement.
Three policy files and a test file.

139
04:20:42,000 --> 04:20:48,000
First, k8s_admission.rego. Pod admission rules.
These run in CI via conftest and optionally at admission via OPA Gatekeeper.

140
04:20:48,000 --> 04:20:54,000
Rule one. No latest image tags in production.
Every image must have a pinned tag.

141
04:20:54,000 --> 04:21:00,000
Rule two. All containers must declare resource requests AND limits.
HPA requires requests. Limits prevent noisy-neighbour OOM on shared nodes.

142
04:21:00,000 --> 04:21:06,000
Rule three. readOnlyRootFilesystem must be true.
Writable root filesystem allows post-exploit persistence.

143
04:21:06,000 --> 04:21:12,000
Rule four. allowPrivilegeEscalation must be false.
Prevents setuid binary escalation.

144
04:21:12,000 --> 04:21:18,000
Rule five. Must not run as root.
runAsNonRoot true at pod level, or runAsUser greater than 0 at container level.

145
04:21:18,000 --> 04:21:24,000
Rule six. No host network, host PID, host IPC.
These grant access to the node's namespaces.

146
04:21:24,000 --> 04:21:30,000
Rule seven. ALL capabilities must be dropped.
Privileged containers are also denied.

147
04:21:30,000 --> 04:21:36,000
Rule eight. Required labels must be present.
app.kubernetes.io/name and app.kubernetes.io/component.

148
04:21:36,000 --> 04:21:42,000
Now helm_policy.rego. Helm manifest rules.
Checks for deprecated Kubernetes APIs.

149
04:21:42,000 --> 04:21:48,000
Rule one. No autoscaling/v2beta1 or batch/v1beta1.
These are removed in Kubernetes 1.29.

150
04:21:48,000 --> 04:21:54,000
Rule two. HPA must use autoscaling/v2.
v1 does not support multi-metric scaling.

151
04:21:54,000 --> 04:22:00,000
Rule three. CronJob must have concurrencyPolicy.
Set to Forbid for ingestion jobs.

152
04:22:00,000 --> 04:22:06,000
Rule four. StatefulSet must have serviceName.
Headless service required for stable DNS.

153
04:22:06,000 --> 04:22:12,000
Now terraform_policy.rego. Infrastructure rules.
Checks Terraform plan JSON for misconfigurations.

154
04:22:12,000 --> 04:22:18,000
Rule one. S3 buckets must block public ACLs.
block_public_acls true, restrict_public_buckets true.

155
04:22:18,000 --> 04:22:24,000
Rule two. S3 encryption required.
Server-side encryption must be configured.

156
04:22:24,000 --> 04:22:30,000
Rule three. RDS must have storage encryption.
storage_encrypted true. Not publicly accessible.

157
04:22:30,000 --> 04:22:36,000
Rule four. RDS must have backup retention.
backup_retention_period at least 1 day.

158
04:22:36,000 --> 04:22:42,000
Rule five. EKS in prod must have private endpoint.
endpoint_public_access false in production.

159
04:22:42,000 --> 04:22:48,000
Rule six. EKS must have secrets encryption with KMS.
encryption_config must be set.

160
04:22:48,000 --> 04:22:54,000
Rule seven. ElastiCache must have at-rest and in-transit encryption.
at_rest_encryption_enabled true, transit_encryption_enabled true.

161
04:22:54,000 --> 04:23:00,000
Rule eight. No SSH or PostgreSQL from 0.0.0.0/0.
Security group rules must restrict access.

162
04:23:00,000 --> 04:23:06,000
Now the k8s_admission_test.rego file.
Unit tests for the admission policy.

163
04:23:06,000 --> 04:23:12,000
Tests cover. latest tag is denied, image with no tag is denied.
Compliant pod passes all 10 checks.

164
04:23:12,000 --> 04:23:18,000
Missing CPU request is denied.
Privileged container is denied.

165
04:23:18,000 --> 04:23:24,000
Run OPA tests with conftest.
Install conftest with brew install conftest or pip install conftest.

166
